<PageLayout
  title="Act I: An Unexpected Fork"
  description="High school jobs, a local computer shop, and a call center in Farmers Branch — the earliest chapter of the career story."
>
  <BackLink href="/career">Back to My Career</BackLink>

  <header class="mb-8">
    <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-brand-600 dark:text-brand-300 mb-1">
      Act I
    </p>
    <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 dark:text-neutral-100">
      An Unexpected Fork
    </h1>
  </header>

  <div
    class="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none prose-a:text-brand-600 dark:prose-a:text-brand-300 prose-blockquote:border-brand-300 dark:prose-blockquote:border-brand-700 prose-code:font-mono prose-code:before:content-none prose-code:after:content-none"
  >
    <p>
      My first job in high school was working in the Outside Garden
      department at Home Depot. I took the job to help pay for my senior
      prom. I have vague memories of the people I worked with, but I
      remember helping customers load lawn mowers, answering questions about
      grills, and trying to figure out which weed killer they actually
      needed.
    </p>

    <p>
      I also spent a short time at Kohl's. I was hired before the store
      officially opened, so as a teenager I got to help set up a brand-new
      location from the ground up. Most of my shifts were spent in the back
      unloading trucks, although I occasionally worked the sales floor or
      registers.
    </p>

    <p>
      Around that same time, I worked for a small local computer shop called
      Happy Computer. We built custom PCs, installed components, replaced
      hardware, and troubleshot whatever problems customers brought through
      the door. It was the first time someone paid me to work with computers
      instead of just tinkering with them at home.
    </p>

    <p>
      While I was a sophomore in college, I landed my first salaried
      position as a Technical Support Representative at EarthLink. The call
      center sat in a two-story building on the corner of LBJ Freeway and
      Luna Road in Farmers Branch. It was surrounded by taller office
      buildings, yet somehow our little building always felt bigger. Every
      shift started the same way. Badge in through the side door. Clock in
      at the computer. Put on the headset. Set my status to "Ready."
    </p>

    <p>The phone would ring.</p>

    <blockquote>
      "Thank you for calling EarthLink. This is Kyle. How can I help you?"
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      Every customer had a case, and every case needed good notes. We
      documented everything we tried so the next person would know exactly
      where things stood if the customer ever had to call back.
    </p>

    <p>
      This was long before we could remote into someone's computer. We had
      to solve every problem through conversation alone. Many customers had
      never used a computer beyond checking email. Some didn't know how to
      double-click. Some didn't know what the desktop was. More than once I
      heard someone read an option aloud as "Install... Yoonistall?"
    </p>

    <p>
      The calls we dreaded most were what we called a TCP/IP R&amp;R, short
      for "Rip and Reinstall." Before we could even begin, we'd have to ask
      if they still had their original Windows 95 or 98 installation CD or
      floppy disks. If they didn't, there wasn't much we could do. If they
      did, we'd reboot the computer, coach them through getting to the DOS
      prompt at just the right moment during startup, and then slowly walk
      them through a long series of commands. Every character mattered, and
      we couldn't see what they were typing.
    </p>

    <p>Computers weren't exactly fast back then. There was a lot of waiting.</p>

    <p>"Has it restarted yet?"</p>

    <p>"Not yet."</p>

    <p>"Okay... we'll wait."</p>

    <p>
      You could almost tell how your shift was going to go by the version of
      Windows the customer was using. If they were running Windows 2000, we
      were thrilled. If they said Windows ME, we quietly cried a little
      inside.
    </p>

    <p>
      We owned every call. Escalations were rare, and it wasn't acceptable
      to tell someone to try a few things and call back later. If a
      customer's dial-up connection wasn't working, it was our job to stay
      with them until it was fixed. I vividly remember one call that lasted
      my entire shift before we finally got everything working.
    </p>

    <p>
      I distinctly remember my team lead, Amir, and coworkers like Ali,
      Stefanie, and Erich. Working second shift meant our lunch break was
      usually a mad dash. We'd pile into Erich's black Honda Prelude, and
      because I was six-foot-two, I always claimed the passenger seat in the
      tiny coupe. We'd crank up Dream Theater, race somewhere to grab food,
      scarf it down, and hurry back before setting our status back to
      "Ready" for the next call.
    </p>

    <p>
      More than twenty-five years later, I still text Erich every year to
      wish him a happy birthday.
    </p>
    
    <h2 id="a-place-of-my-own">A Place of My Own</h2>
    
    <p>
      I don't know exactly why I left EarthLink. What I do know is that I
      found myself out of work for a little while.
    </p>

    <p>
      To help me get by, my dad agreed to renovate my friend's mom's garage
      into a studio apartment. Instead of getting paid, he horsetraded for
      my rent, and I helped him with some of the work. That project taught
      me a few things. I learned how much I hate hanging drywall and
      spreading mud. I learned that accidentally grabbing 240 volts can make
      your arm go limp for a few minutes. I even learned how to install a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Packaged_terminal_air_conditioner" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PTAC</a> next
      to a brand-new exterior door.
    </p>

    <p>
      I loved living in that little garage apartment. The PTAC kept the
      place ice cold, which was exactly how I liked it. It was the first
      place that was truly my own. My first <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentium_4" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Pentium 4</a> sat in the corner of
      that room. It was also where I watched the Twin Towers fall on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/September_11_attacks" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">September 11</a>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The daughter of my dad's best friend helped me land a job at a pool
      supply store in Plano. My manager was Ken, and I worked alongside his
      son and daughter. We were a tight-knit group, and I quickly discovered
      there was an entire world of pool equipment that I had never thought
      about before. I found it strangely satisfying to keep track of
      inventory, making sure we had enough impellers for the common pumps,
      grids for Pentair <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diatomaceous_earth_filtration" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">D.E.</a> filters, wheels and ball bearings for the <a href="https://www.polarispool.com/en/products/pool-cleaners/pressure-automatic-pool-cleaners/polaris-vac-sweep-360" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Polaris 360</a>,
      and staying in touch with our supplier, SCP.
    </p>

    <p>
      Before long, it became clear that I had a knack for computers. The
      company's IT Manager was the one who really entrusted me with
      technical responsibilities, giving me opportunities to troubleshoot
      systems and step into that role more seriously. At the same time, Ken
      trusted me in a different way. Whenever something went wrong with the
      point-of-sale system, the thermal receipt printer, an executive's
      laptop, or the network, I'd usually get the first crack at fixing it.
      But beyond that, he trusted me personally, not just as an employee,
      but as someone he could rely on. Those little detours into IT quickly
      became my favorite part of the job.
    </p>

    <p>
      On January 1, 2002, I moved into my own one-bedroom apartment. It was
      about 500 square feet, on the first floor, just a few minutes from the
      pool store. The weather was dreary that day, and my mom helped me move
      everything in. I mostly slept on the couch because I thought it was
      more comfortable than the bed.
    </p>

    <p>
      The pool industry hit a rough patch, and I was laid off. It was the
      first time it had happened to me, and it took a while to process. At
      the same time, I understood the decision. Most of the company was
      family. I wasn't.
    </p>

    <p>
      About a month later, I accepted a technical support position at
      TelVista supporting <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/QuickBooks" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">QuickBooks</a>. After a week or two of training, it
      felt a lot like being back at EarthLink. The biggest difference was
      that we could reach out to a higher tier for ideas if we got stuck.
      One of my teammates had long fingernails because he was an incredible <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flamenco" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">flamenco</a>
      guitar player. It was the first time I had ever heard of flamenco.
    </p>

    <p>
      TelVista only lasted about five months. It never quite felt like the
      right fit, and my friend Derrick let me know about an opening at <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experian" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Experian</a>
      in Allen that paid more.
    </p>

    <p>
      Experian was different from anywhere else I had worked. I could wear
      whatever I wanted, so I usually showed up in punk band T-shirts,
      oversized <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JNCO" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">JNCO</a> jeans, dark blue hair, and piercings in my ears and
      lip. During training we processed mail all day, and somehow I became
      ridiculously fast at it. By the time we graduated and joined the rest
      of the department, people already knew who I was. The blue hair
      probably helped.
    </p>

    <p>
      Once we hit the floor, we'd rotate between processing mail requests
      and helping customers over the phone. I always preferred the mail
      because we could put on headphones and listen to music while we
      worked. My catty-corner cubemate, Ed, introduced me to bands I had
      never heard before like <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stabbing_Westward" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Stabbing Westward</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dishwalla" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Dishwalla</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eve_6" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Eve 6</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guster" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Guster</a>,
      and plenty of others. More than twenty years later, whenever "<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Right_Now_(SR-71_song)" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Right Now</a>"
      by SR-71 comes on, I'm immediately back in that cubicle because Ed
      took the time to hand me his CD binder.
    </p>

    <p>
      Derrick expanded my playlist even more. He introduced me to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_October" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Blue October</a>
      and a local Dallas band called <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edgewater_(band)" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Edgewater</a>. We saw Blue October together
      at least twice, including a show at The Aardvark in Fort Worth. We
      also caught Edgewater several times at Club Clearview in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deep_Ellum,_Dallas" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Deep Ellum</a>.
      Those bands became the soundtrack of that season of my life, and I
      still think of those concerts whenever they come up in a playlist.
    </p>

    <p>
      Derrick also taught me how to drive a stick shift. His <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chevrolet_S-10" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Chevy S-10</a>
      needed a little extra gas when taking off, and he had far more
      patience than I deserved while I ground the gears. We'd drive to work
      together, hang out after work, and he eventually trusted me enough to
      drive his truck even when he wasn't in it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Even though I wasn't at Experian very long, the people stayed with
      me. Derrick, Skye, Ed, Alina, Lori, Josh, and Camilla all became part
      of that chapter of my life.
    </p>

    <p>
      I had no idea that someone from an earlier chapter was about to
      change the direction of the next one.
    </p>

    <p class="not-prose text-sm text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400 italic">
      More to come, including the move to Hanson.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageLayout>
